This was a freedom of satire which goes back to Ennius. Indeed, many of Vergil's ex- amples are undoubted imitations of Ennius, or else intended to give a touch of the antique. This is especially true of v111. which through such a famous line as Vergil, Aen. VI, 840 :

Unus qui nobis cunctando restituis rem,

must have suggested Ennius and the old poets to many of Juvenal's hearers. In some cases at least the antique and solemn touch, used seriously or satirically according to thc author’s mood at the time, seems to have been felt. Com- pare 1, 108, 1593 2, 28, 132 3 3, 90, 191, 2033 5, 20, 88, 114; 6, 32, 309; 7, 2083 8, 9, 62, 112-; 10, 82, 119, 225, etc. In others, and possibly in some which I have just mentioned, the touch was not so much the antique and solemn (serious or otherwise) as the plain, old-fashioned, and homely. The tetrasyllabic cadence,

IX. Cum populum gregibus comitum premit hic spoliator,

was, as we saw, a rule of the Catullian versus spondiacus. Otherwise it is extremely rare, and chiefly confined to satire and the early poets. Manitius gives Lucretius 153 cases3 Vergil 513 Horace 343 Juvenal 55. The word is usually a proper name, except in Lucretius, who has none. Juvenal imitates the freedom of Lucretius in this respect. Also he frequently neglects the rule of a preceding mono- syllable.
